const intro = "There’s a reason Asian Americans, like Haimei, get so excited when we see ourselves represented: For much of US history, Asian American characters in popular media were meant to mock us. The early 1900s saw white actors donning [“yellowface”](https://www.history.com/news/yellowface-whitewashing-in-film-america) to play some of the most prominent Asian characters, including Charlie Chan, Dr. Fu Manchu and Mr. Yunioshi. Exaggerated racial features—including slanted eyes, yellow skin color, black hair, and an “Asian” accent—were common.\r\n\r\n\r\n>> Breakfast_at_Mr_Yunioshis.gif | Breakfast_at_Mr_Yunioshis.gif | Mickey Rooney plays Mr. Yunioshi in yellowface | Mickey Rooney plays Mr. Yunioshi in <i>Breakfast at Tiffany's</i> (1961) Source: GifRun\r\n\r\n\r\nWhen Asian American actors were finally cast to play Asian characters, they were often portrayed through stereotypes, like Bruce Lee being confined to martial arts roles or Nancy Kwan repeatedly cast as a “Dragon Lady.”\r\n\r\n\r\n>> nancy-kwan.png | nancy-kwan.png | Nancy Kwan plays Suzie Wong in The World of Suzie Wong (1960) | Nancy Kwan plays Suzie Wong in <i>The World of Suzie Wong</i> (1960)\r\n\r\n\r\nBut these days, Asian actors no longer play stereotypes; they are full characters—love interests, superheroes, and even the modern-day American family.\r\n\r\n\r\nYet there’s more to it than just portraying characters. Asian Americans come from dozens of countries with even more unique ethnic identities. When the characters inaccurately portray those aspects of our identity, we notice. And it’s not just us. A [study published in 2025](https://www.mckinsey.com/featured-insights/diversity-and-inclusion/from-margins-to-mainstream-asians-and-pacific-islanders-in-hollywood) showed that less than 30% of Asian and Pacific Islanders feel like they are represented in the media.\r\n\r\n\r\nThat’s partially because, according to a [2023 poll by the Pew Research Center](https://www.pewresearch.org/race-and-ethnicity/2023/05/08/diverse-cultures-and-shared-experiences-shape-asian-american-identities/), many Asian Americans feel more closely aligned with their specific ethnicity, like “Chinese” or “Thai,” rather than broadly “Asian.” So it’s especially exciting to see our specific customs, cuisines, and languages reflected on the big screen.\r\n\r\n\r\n>> ChartAAPI.svg | ChartAAPI-mobile.svg | How Asian Americans identify themselves | Data source: Pew Research Center, Survey of Asian American adults conducted 2022 - 2023 | How Asian Americans identify themselves\r\n\r\n\r\nIt’s difficult to judge whether a character fairly portrays a specific ethnicity, but we can assess whether an actor and the character they portray share the same ethnicity as a baseline for accurate representation.\r\n\r\n\r\nTo explore this actor-character mismatch further, we compiled more than 3,500 films from 1982 to 2023 featuring Asian actors. We identified films where Asian actors played a major role, getting us to 500 films. From there, we filtered the list down to films where the character’s Asian ethnicity was a notable part of the storyline; we wanted to focus on media where we were supposed to feel represented but didn’t due to these inaccuracies. \r\n\r\n\r\nFor example, *The Life of Pi (2012)* qualified because the protagonist, Pi, struggles with his Hindu faith and Indian heritage along with other reflections. However, *Jumanji: The Next Level (2019)* did not; while the character Dr. Bravestone is played by Samoan actor Dwayne “The Rock” Johnson, the plot does not reference the character’s Asian identity at all. \r\n\r\n\r\nUltimately we found **80 films** with **160 Asian actors** playing **236 characters**.\r\n\r\n\r\nWhile we covered a wide breadth of movies, our criteria for including movies was based on having high profile actors in the cast or reaching a moderate threshold for box office earnings, so it’s possible we missed some movies.";
